{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f5c4fe54-8b08-418e-abfc-699c4cfc1df0","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2, which supports the modern approach. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IDisposable, IAsyncDisposable\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = default!;\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public void Setup()\n    {\n        // Synchronous init\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init — both run before each test\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest() { }\n\n    public void Dispose() { /* sync cleanup */ }\n    public ValueTask DisposeAsync() { /* async cleanup */ }\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n- **TestContext**: Declare a public settable property — MSTest injects it automatically (no constructor needed).\n- **Sync + Async init**: You can have multiple `[TestInitialize]` methods; the sync one runs first, then the async one.\n- **Cleanup**: Implement `IDisposable`/`IAsyncDisposable`, or use `[TestCleanup]` methods similarly.\n\nFor **class-level** (one-time) init, use `[ClassInitialize]` (must be `static`) and `[ClassCleanup]`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1003c614-ee2a-472a-9ab4-489a355c8ee2","outputTokens":314,"requestId":"BC2A:48F1C:1DFCBAE:213C034:69FA976A"},"id":"ef249112-0ef9-4650-85e2-c6f30e6d63eb","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:20:50.717Z","parentId":"496a2f82-0597-4afd-b270-05e7ed4a8ed8"}
